## STEP 36: Run Ablation Study (INT4, INT16 variants)

The paper includes Table 2 (ablation on bit-width). You need to run additional experiments for INT4 and INT16 quantization.

Create `experiments/run_ablation.py`:

```
For each bit-width in [4, 8, 16, 32]:
    - If 32: this is the Standard FL baseline (already run)
    - If 8: this is TeleZK-FL (already run)
    - If 4 or 16: need new runs
    
For INT4:
    - Modify ptq.py to support 4-bit quantization
    - qmin = -8, qmax = 7 (16 values)
    - LUT size: 16 × 16 = 256 entries (tiny)
    - Run CheXpert IID with 1 seed (42) for 50 rounds
    - Expected: AUC drops significantly (~0.81-0.82)

For INT16:
    - qmin = -32768, qmax = 32767
    - LUT would be 65536 × 65536 = 4 billion entries (too large!)
    - For INT16, skip the LUT approach and use standard arithmetic
    - The proof time will be much slower than INT8
    - Run CheXpert IID with 1 seed (42) for 50 rounds
    - Expected: AUC nearly identical to FP32 (~0.864)

For each bit-width, also measure:
    - Proof generation time (for the full model)
    - Memory usage (approximate from tensor sizes)

Save results to results/logs/ablation_{bits}bit.json
```

